<typeStatus box="[1295,1389,1641,1665]" pageId="16" pageNumber="119">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="120" pageId="16" pageNumber="119" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,1737,2082]" pageId="16" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[831,961,1737,1761]" pageId="16" pageNumber="119">Description</emphasis>
: Body length 
<quantity box="[1128,1212,1737,1761]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="16" pageNumber="119" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 1.0 mm. Habitus slender (
<figureCitation box="[1110,1172,1769,1793]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="6.[189,229,1981,2003]" captionTargetBox="[195,1433,232,1956]" captionTargetId="figure-94@6.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 1–8: Male habitusof Leptusaspp.1 – L.excisa; 2 – L.grandipennis; 3– L.auriculata; 4– L.gonggana; 5– L.emeiana; 6 – L. jizuica;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743066" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743066/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="119">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Colouration (note that the 
<typeStatus box="[877,971,1801,1825]" pageId="16" pageNumber="119">holotype</typeStatus>
is slightly teneral]: head blackish-brown; pronotum brown; elytra dark-yellow with the scutellar region diffusely darker; abdomen pale-brown with tergite VI and the anterior portions of tergites V and VII darker; legs yellow; antennae pale-brown with the basal three antennomeres dark-yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,1737,2082]" lastBlockId="17.[151,757,233,961]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="120" pageId="16" pageNumber="119">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[905,980,1993,2017]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="119">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as broad; punctation very coarse and dense, interstices reduced to narrow ridges. Eyes longer than postocular region in lateral view. Antenna slender; antennomeres IV weakly oblong, V–VI approximately as long as broad, VII–X increasing in width and increasingly transverse, and X barely 1.5 times as broad as long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,757,233,961]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[277,351,361,385]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.3 times as broad as long and 1.25 times as broad as head; maximal width in anterior half; posterior angles obtusely marked; punctation as coarse and as dense as that of head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,757,233,961]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[233,307,489,513]" captionStart="Figs 9–18" captionStartId="7.[151,191,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[153,1398,232,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-113@7.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 9–18: Male habitus (9–11) and forebody (12–18) of Leptusa spp. 9, 15 – L. habana; 10 – L. monscangi; 11 – L. pathibarana; 12 – L. excisa; 13 – L. grandipennis; 14 – L. gonggana; 16 – L. auriculata; 17 – L. jizuica; 18 – L. desculpens. Scale bars:9–16: 1.0 mm; 17–18: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5743070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5743070/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) slightly longer than pronotum; punctation as dense as, and even coarser than that of pronotum. Abdomen narrower than elytra; tergites III–V with anterior impressions densely and coarsely punctate; punctation on remainder of tergal surfaces moderately fine and moderately dense; interstices with distinct microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII with narrow palisade fringe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,757,233,961]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
: tergites VII and VIII unmodified (Fig. 59); posterior margin of sternite VIII obtusely produced in the middle (Fig. 60); median lobe of aedeagus (Fig. 58) approximately 
<quantity box="[231,326,841,865]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="17" pageNumber="120" unit="mm" value="0.25">0.25 mm</quantity>
long, with ventral process and internal structures of distinctive shapes; apical lobe of paramere rather short.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,757,233,961]" box="[151,294,937,961]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">: unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,756,1001,1185]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,360,1001,1025]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: This species is readily distinguished from all other congeners recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[609,674,1033,1057]" name="China" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">China</collectingCountry>
by the distinctive shapes of the ventral process and the internal structures of the aedeagus and additionally by the combination of small size, slender habitus, and conspicuously coarse punctation of the forebody.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="120" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,756,1225,1313]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,522,1225,1249]" pageId="17" pageNumber="120">Distribution and natural history</emphasis>
